  <h4>Program Notes</h4>
  <p><span class=3D"bignum">1.</span>When you run the program you will see =
the main program window shown here.=20
  Use any units you like, as long as you use the same units for both the De=
pth and Diameter. You can also
  select Diameter and f/D as inputs using the <span class=3D"alert">Options=
 &gt; Select Inputs</span> menu choice. I recommend using=20
  smaller units: inches instead of feet, or millimeters instead of meters, =
to increase the resolution of your=20
  measurements.</p>  =20
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
   <img alt=3D"Main Program Window" src=3D"https://mscir.tripod.com/parabol=
a/images/1.gif" height=3D"381" width=3D"760">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">2.</span> After you enter some numbers into the Di=
ameter and=20
  Depth text boxes and click the <span class=3D"alert">Calculate</span> but=
ton, the program=20
  will show you the scaled down shape of the parabola you described, and it=
 will calculate=20
  the (x, y) coordinates of the curve of the parabola in 16 straight line s=
egments. You can=20
  calculate the (x, y) coordinates using anywhere from 2 to 1000 segments.
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Enter Inputs into Main Program Window" src=3D"https://mscir.t=
ripod.com/parabola/images/2.gif" height=3D"381" width=3D"760">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">3.</span> To see what the shape and focal length w=
ould look like=20
  when the depth is increased to 18, hold down the horizontal scroll bar ne=
xt to the text box=20
  and watch the parabola's shape change.
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Change Inputs in Main Program Window" src=3D"https://mscir.tr=
ipod.com/parabola/images/3.gif" height=3D"381" width=3D"760">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">4.</span> If you click the <span class=3D"alert">S=
ave to Text File</span>
  button, the program will prompt you to select a folder and enter a filena=
me, and then it writes a file with the=20
  information you see in the text box on the right. Here's  how the saved f=
ile looks when it is opened using Windows=20
  Notepad (using the Lucida Console <a href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Typeface#Proportion" target=3D"_blank" title=3D"Read about non-proportiona=
l fonts at Wikipedia">non-proportional</a> font where all characters have t=
he same=20
  width so the columns line up vertically). The program will automatically =
suggest a filename that includes depth and=20
  diameter but you can enter any filename you like.
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Saved Text File" src=3D"https://mscir.tripod.com/parabola/ima=
ges/4.gif" height=3D"348" width=3D"339">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">5.</span> If you'd like to see the coefficients of=
 the Equation that=20
  describes the current Parabola, use the menu choice: <span class=3D"alert=
">File &gt; View=20
  the Coefficients.</span> You will see a message box like this one showing=
 you the values=20
  used in the parabola equation:
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Menu Choice to see Parabola Coefficients" src=3D"https://msci=
r.tripod.com/parabola/images/5.gif" height=3D"357" width=3D"275">
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img src=3D"https://mscir.tripod.com/parabola/images/5a.gif" height=3D"26=
3" width=3D"404" alt=3D"Parabola coefficients">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">6.</span> If you move your cursor over the image o=
f the parabola,
  you will see the individual points calculated by the program: the (x, y) =
coordinates=20
  are shown at the bottom of the display. The point (horizontally) closest =
to the mouse=20
  cursor will be shown, you can see the location of each point listed in th=
e text box.
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Viewing the (x,y) coordinates on the Graphic" src=3D"https://=
mscir.tripod.com/parabola/images/6.gif" height=3D"381" width=3D"760">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">7.</span> There are several file output formats yo=
u can use to save
  the data to a file that can be read by another program like ACAD, CorelDr=
aw, or MS Excel.
  You can see these menu choices under the <b>File</b> menu. =20
  <p>You can print the graphic of the parabola to a printer using the <b>Pr=
int</b> menu choice.
  </p><p>You can change the foreground and background color of the Parabola=
 graphic using the
  <b>Options</b> menu choice. =20
</p></div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">8.</span> Wifi Calculations for centered or offset=
 feedhorn dishes
  can be done using the <span class=3D"alert">Wifi Calculations</span> menu=
 choice.
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv">
  <img alt=3D"Wifi Centered Feedhorn Calculations" src=3D"https://mscir.tri=
pod.com/parabola/images/centeredfeedhorn.gif" height=3D"190" width=3D"712">
  <br><br><img alt=3D"Wifi Offset Feedhorn Calculations" src=3D"https://msc=
ir.tripod.com/parabola/images/offsetfeedhorn.gif" height=3D"548" width=3D"5=
50">
</div>
<div class=3D"contentdiv">
  <span class=3D"bignum">9.</span> If you'd like to read more about Solar C=
ollectors and Solar Cooking Projects,=20
  or about the math behind Parabolas, click the menu choice:
  <br><span class=3D"alert">File &gt; Parabola and Solar Project Websites</=
span>.=20
  <br>Click on a website and it will load into your default web browser aut=
omatically. Click the <span class=3D"alert">Hide</span>=20
  button to view the main program form again when you're finished with the =
web sites. <a href=3D"https://mscir.tripod.com/parabola/solar_links.htm"> A=
 collection of these links can be found here.</a>
</div>
<div class=3D"imgdiv2">
  <img alt=3D"Web Sites About Parabolas" src=3D"https://mscir.tripod.com/pa=
rabola/images/8.gif" height=3D"381" width=3D"760">
</div>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
